          <tr><td>Dàxuě</td><td>大雪</td><td>Dec 7</td><td>Jié</td><td>Major Snow &mdash; Heavy snowfall. Rivers freeze. The custom of &ldquo;sealing the plough&rdquo; (<span class="chinese-char">封犁</span>) marked the end of the farming year.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dōngzhì</td><td>冬至</td><td>Dec 22</td><td>Qì</td><td>Winter Solstice &mdash; Shortest day. In Zhou and Han times, this was the start of the new year. Grand court ceremonies were held; officials exchanged formal greetings.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Xiǎohán</td><td>小寒</td><td>Jan 6</td><td>Jié</td><td>Minor Cold &mdash; Cold intensifies. The &ldquo;Nine Nines&rdquo; counting custom (<span class="chinese-char">數九</span>) begins from the Winter Solstice, tracking 81 days until spring.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dàhán</td><td>大寒</td><td>Jan 20</td><td>Qì</td><td>Major Cold &mdash; Coldest period. <a href="/spring-festival/">Spring Festival</a> preparations commence. The cycle completes and returns to Lìchūn.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="callout-box callout-box--jade">
        <div class="callout-icon">🌿</div>
        <div class="callout-content">
          <h3>Five Elements & Agricultural Wisdom</h3>
          <p>Each season of six terms corresponds to a <a href="/wuxing/">Five Element</a>: Spring/Wood, Summer/Fire, Autumn/Metal, Winter/Water, with Earth governing 18-day transitions. Proverbs like <span class="chinese-char">清明前後，種瓜點豆</span> ("Around Qingming, plant melons and sow beans") encode generations of empirical knowledge. Xu Guangqi's Ming Dynasty <em>Nongzheng Quanshu</em> (1639) synthesised centuries of regional farming mapped to each term.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

